The '''Dark Force''' was the [[Dark side of the Force/Legends|dark side]] religion that sprang up around the [[Dark Force Temple]], an ancient [[Sith/Legends|Sith]] temple on [[Dromund Kaas/Legends|Dromund Kaas]]. It followed the teachings of [[Plaristes]] and [[Dak Ramis]].

==History==
===Millennial's heresy===
{{Quote|Its next round of rediscovery came by someone who rejected the Rule of Two, who thought that there was more than enough of the dark side to go around. He founded a religion that would become known as the Dark Force. There's an ancient temple there still. It was serviced for centuries by the Dark Prophets. It's so steeped in the dark side that it formed its own nexus-one so powerful it interferes with all weaponry and technology except for lightsabers.|[[Luke Skywalker/Legends|Luke Skywalker]], about Dromund Kaas and Darth Millennial|<ref name="Fate of the Jedi: Ascension">''[[Fate of the Jedi: Ascension]]''</ref>}}
[[File:Darthmill.jpg|thumb|right|200px|[[Darth Millennial]], founder of the Dark Force.]]
The Dark Force cult emerged nearly a thousand [[Standard year/Legends|years]] before the [[Battle of Yavin/Legends|Battle of Yavin]]. At the [[Time/Legends|time]], the reigning [[Dark Lord of the Sith/Legends|Dark Lord of the Sith]] were [[Darth Cognus]] and her [[Sith apprentice/Legends|disciple]], the three-[[Eye/Legends|eyed]] mutant [[Darth Millennial]]. As members of the [[Order of the Sith Lords|Banite Sith]], they followed the [[Rule of Two/Legends|Rule of Two]], which decreed that only two Sith could exist at any given time: the [[Sith Master/Legends|master]] and his or her apprentice. Millennial, however, came to find that doctrine too restrictive. While he had often been at odds with his master, Millennial rebelled against the teachings of Cognus once too many. Barely escaping the confrontation with Cognus, Millennial took refuge on [[Dromund Kaas/Legends|Dromund Kaas]], a [[Planet/Legends|planet]] that had a long history with the Sith. In his new haven, Millennial kept meditating on the teachings of the Sith while also studying the works of [[Plaristes]] and [[Dak Ramis]], two controversial philosophers who had lived [[25,053 BBY|over 25,000 years]] earlier.<ref name="END">{{Hyperspace|url=hyperspace/member/insideronline/88/indexp2.html|text=''Evil Never Dies: The Sith Dynasties''|int=Evil Never Dies: The Sith Dynasties}}</ref>

Millennial came to regard himself as a prophet chosen by the will of the Force itself. He founded a new sect he called the Dark Force, anointing himself the [[Supreme Prophet]] of the Dark Side. His philosophy, which drew on Millennial's Sith roots as well as on Plaristes' and Ramis' writings, started to attract many followers. While some of the new cultists were intellectually brilliant, many of them were much more naïve. At any rate, those who called into question the Dark Force tenets were condemned to [[Death/Legends|death]] for heresy.<ref name="END" />
When Millennial ended up passing away, his cult survived him.<ref name="END" /> In the second [[Standard century/Legends|century]] before the [[Battle of Yavin/Legends|Battle of Yavin]], even a [[Jedi/Legends|Jedi]] [[Padawan/Legends|Padawan]] named [[Kibh Jeen]] was seduced by the Dark Force's philosophy,<ref name="END" /> although he was taken down in a [[Final battle of the Dark Jedi Conflict|space battle]]<ref name="LFCG">''[[Living Force Campaign Guide]]''</ref> in [[181 BBY/Legends|181 BBY]].<ref name="JeenDate">The ''[[Living Force Campaign Guide]]'' states that [[Kibh Jeen]] died 149 [[Standard year/Legends|years]] before the [[Invasion of Naboo/Legends|Invasion of Naboo]], an event that is dated to [[32 BBY/Legends|32 BBY]] by ''[[The New Essential Chronology]]''. His death can therefore be placed in [[181 BBY/Legends|181 BBY]].</ref> At some point, the fallen Jedi [[Kadann]] and his pupil [[Jedgar]] traveled to Dromund Kaas, where they discovered the Dark Force Temple. The two elected to join the cult.<ref name="DSS">''[[The Dark Side Sourcebook]]''</ref>

===The Emperor's Mages===
{{Quote|The future you see isn't yours. You are merely the messenger. Serve me. Become my prophet. Reveal the will of the Force as you see it and I will make your predictions come true.|Darth Sidious, to Kadann|<ref name="DSS" />}}
At some point before the fall of the Galactic Republic, the Dark Force prophets were visited by [[Palpatine/Legends|Darth Sidious]], the last of the Banite Sith. Intrigued by the prophets' unique view of the Force and interested in their ucanny ability to predict the future, Sidious decided to turn them to his service. He convinced Prophet Kadann that the future he saw was not his, that he was only a messenger. By serving him and his long-percolating scheme to rule the galaxy, the Prophets of the Dark Side would fulfill their true mission.<ref name="DSS" /> By pleding allegiance to Sidious, the clergymen of the Dark Force were brought back into the fold of the Banite Sith.<ref name="END" /> Sidious annexed the Prophets as his [[Advisor/Legends|advisors]], and Kadann was appointed the Supreme Prophet of the Dark Side. Some years later, Sidious' plans came to fruition as he replaced the [[Galactic Republic/Legends|Galactic Republic]] with his [[Galactic Empire/Legends|First Galactic Empire]].<ref name="ROS">{{Film|III}}</ref>

With the advent of his [[New Order/Legends|New Order]], the Sith Lord turned [[Galactic Emperor/Legends|Galactic Emperor]] named the prophets the [[Prophets of the Dark Side|Emperor's Mages]], collectively forming the [[Prophets of the Dark Side|Secret Order of the Empire]]. Many of the Emperor's [[Dark Jedi/Legends|Dark Jedi]], Jedi-hunting [[Inquisitorius/Legends|Inquisitors]], [[Force-sensitive/Legends|Force-sensitive]] military officers, and [[Emperor's Hand/Legends|Emperor's Hands]] received their first exposure to the dark side by studying the Dark Force religion on Dromund Kaas under the tutelage of the Prophets.<ref name="END" /> While Kadann remained the Supreme Prophet, other significant figures emerged in the cult. Among them was [[Lord/Legends|Lord]] [[Cronal]], a particularly cruel and twisted Human [[Sorcerers of Rhand|warlock]]<ref name="EP">{{GamerCite|5|The Emperor's Pawns}}</ref> who may have been sired by a [[Dathomir/Legends|Dathomiri]] [[Witch/Legends|witch]].<ref name="Imperial">{{SW|url=news/the-imperial-warlords-despoilers-of-an-empire-part-3|series=The Imperial Warlords: Despoilers of an Empire|text=Part 3|nolive=1}}</ref> The former [[Jedi archaeologist]] [[Jerec (Inquisitor)|Jerec]] also studied the Dark Force religion, and he cultivated a close bond with Cronal.<ref name="The Dark Forces Saga 6">{{Wizards|url=default.asp?x=starwars/article/sw20050616a|series=The Dark Forces Saga|text=Part 6: Outcasts and Megalomaniacs Welcome}}</ref> Finally, Kadann's apprentice Jedgar was named [[High Prophet]].<ref name="END" />

===Loyalty schism===
Although Palpatine had appointed Kadann to the position of Supreme Prophet, the man's true loyalty still lay with the Dark Force. Prior to the [[Battle of Endor/Legends|Battle of Endor]], Kadann's visions indicated a probable restoration of balance to the Force. While that prophecy did not settle well with Palpatine, Kadann refused to compromise. He was forced to flee the Emperor's wrath with some of the Mages, while others remained behind with the Emperor. Those who sided with the Emperor were led by Lord Cronal.<ref name="EP" /> As Kadann and his ecclesiastic followers fled to their Supreme Prophet's stronghold on [[Bosthirda/Legends|Bosthirda]], the Dark Temple on Dromund Kaas was abandoned.<ref name="The Dark Forces Saga 5">{{Wizards|url=default.asp?x=starwars/article/sw20050609a|series=The Dark Forces Saga|text=Part 5: Two Peas in a Pod}}</ref>

